            {
                "s2_paper_id": "e5148d3a0e499464e715c6d671520a7b7e9575b1",
                "title": "A Case Study for Exploring the Impact of Optimized K - Means Algorithm on the Energy Efficiency of Multicore Systems",
                "year": 2023,
                "venue": "2023 IEEE International Conference on High Performance Computing & Communications, Data Science & Systems, Smart City & Dependability in Sensor, Cloud & Big Data Systems & Application (HPCC/DSS/SmartCity/DependSys)",
                "citation_count": 0,
                "reference_count": 20,
                "abstract": "Cluster-based manycore system is a practical design for manufacturing the multicore systems. In this design, cores are divided into multiple clusters, where cores within a cluster share the same VoltagelFrequency (V/F) level. Each of clusters may have distinct V/F level compared to the others. Because all cores of a cluster share the same V/F level, it is critical that the size of a cluster would not be much bigger or smaller compared to the other clusters. This is because the uneven distribution of cores among clusters negatively impacts the energy efficiency: speeding up underloaded clusters wastes energy and slowing down overloaded clusters delays runtime. In this paper, we present a case study to optimize the functionality of the K - Means algorithm for improving the performance of a multi -core system. Among the existing clustering algorithms, we chose K-Means because of its simple design and broad use in various disciplines. The standard K - Means clusters cores with similar workloads that differ in computation from one phase to another. However, clusters formed by K-Means vary in size, putting too many cores inside some clusters while leaving others with very few cores. To address the balance of clusters, we use an existing variation of K - Means (constrained K-Means) that defines a lower bound for the number of cores in each of clusters. Constraining the size of each cluster of the multicore system creates the balanced clusters, where the sizes of clusters are almost identical. To measure the energy efficiency of the applied clustering, this paper suggests a Dynamic Voltage and Frequency Scaling (DVFS) methodology that adjusts the V/F levels of clusters at each phase of an application. For several multi-threaded applications, results show that at the best case the constrained K - Means improves the Energy-Delay Product (EDP) up to 40% compared to the standard version. The results also show that on average across all applications the constrained K-Means improves EDP in a range between 5% and 30% compared to the related works. The outcome of this study provides a guideline for chip manufacturers to analyze a tradeoff between using more hardware to adjust the speed of clusters and increasing the energy efficiency at an acceptable level.",
                "authors": [
